and probably from the old Euboean colony of Cumae in Campania (hence called Cumaean, or, as here, Euboicus) : the old story was that the Sibyl herself offered nine books for sale to king Tarquin; being refused, she burnt three, offcring the rest for the same price. After a second refusal she came back again, having burnt three more, and the remaining three were purchased for the original sum. They were kept strictly secret, and were consulted in time of trouble by order of the Senate. When the temple of Iuppiter was burnt in 82 (cf. 18), a new Sibylline collection was made and kept in the restored temple.

213. Semo, Sancus, or Dius Fidius [clearly ‘the god of Faith or Honour’, from fides or sancio] was a very ancient Sabine deity, whose temple was on the N. W. edge of the Quirinal hill. It contained many old relies, and among others a wooden shield covered with oxhide, on which was written in old characters a treaty between Tarquin the Proud and Gabii.
